Dec 28 2008 	Great hotel on Dubai Creek	We spent 2 nights at this hotel over Christmas and enjoyed it thoroughly. Good location within walking distance of the Gold Souk and a short walk along the waterfront to the waterbus over to Dubai Museum and the old quarter. Taxis to the other main sights in Dubai (e.g. Dubai Mall, Mall of the Emirates) were inexpensive. We spent an hour in a traffic jam and the metre barely budged. Our two rooms were in the Tower and included an excellent breakfast buffet in the executive lounge on the main floor plus free drinks before dinner. We ate one night in the Italian restaurant and had good food and service for a reasonable price. We also ate in the English Pub on the main level but found the food of inferior quality and the drinks over-priced. A bottle of water was almost the same price as the beer.Rooms were large, clean and well appointed, and price very reasonable by Dubai standards. The hotel was quiet over the holidays and our rooms were upgraded to suites, with complimentary fruit basket and bottle of wine. Personnel throughout the hotel were efficient and courteous, especially the bellmen. Our rate also included pick up and drop off at the airport. We would definitely stay there on our next trip.	
Dec 10 2008 	$32/day for Internet!	I arrived for what was supposed to be a 3-night stay. Check in was easy with no wait, although the offset chairs at the check-in desks are a little awkward. I prefer an old-fashioned check-in desk. My travel companions were Starwood Gold using points for a free stay and they were upgraded to an upper-floor creek view. I am a normal level Starwood preferred guest and was not automatically upgraded, contrary to what other reviewers have said. I was given a first-floor room with a view over the front of the hotel. Nice room - good bathroom, great shower, comfy beds. However, the location was awful. I barely slept, with the noise of guests in the lobby, then what sounded like someone pounding rocks, then with the sound of vacuuming in the lobby for several hours - may have been normal cleaning, may have been special work? Anyway, stay away from first floor rooms overlooking the lobby if you want to sleep.My first morning I learned that I would have to fly home that evening due to a family emergency. The hotel was very accommodating and waived any fees for checking out early. They even gave me a complementary late checkout. I left luggage with the bellman for a few hours with no problems. Very easy to get cabs from the front. The internet, as others have noted, is ludicrously expensive. 120 AED a day, which is $32/day. There is no excuse for this - that's more than I pay for a month at home. Services in Dubai are expensive, but not that expensive - it costs the hotel nothing incrementally to have more guests logged on. Next time I am going to verify internet rates in advance and not stay anywhere that charges over $10-15/day. Gauging your customers on small things like internet (or mini-bar) is a good way not to get repeat business.So nice hotel - if they bring their internet charges back down to a reasonable level I would consider staying there again. And I would pay a little more for a creek view - anything but a 1st floor lobby-overlooking room would be better.	
Nov 26 2008 	Lovely Creek Hotel	My wife and I stayed at the Sheraton Dubai Creek Hotel and Towers at the beginning of November. In summary the hotel stay was really nice and I would probably stay there again...We stay on the 9th floor in a Towers Room. In the room it tells you that the rate is 3200Dhs/night for a Towers Room and about Dhs850 for a normal room.The Towers room was massive, full size bed, LCD TV, DVD player, Hairdryer, Sofa and Armchair, Coffee machine (as part of minibar). The view out of the window was pretty amazing as well, as we had a room that overlooked the Creek.The bathroom is quite large, the shower is powerful, and the mirror is heated so it doesnt steam up!You also get access to the towers lounge, which is a large quite with a few sofas, single computer internet access, and a TV. Here you have access to complimentary coffee, tea and non-alcholic drinks. Canapes are served around tea time, and complimentary alcohol is served between 6.30-8pm.We got this at a discounted price, but I wouldn't have paid the full whack for it.Breakfast is served in the Towers Lounge (continental) or in the italian restaurant in the lobby (full range of items). The atmosphere downstairs is much better, and you have the option of seating on the terrace above the pool over looking the Creek.The Service of the staff is flawless. We had an early flight, and so the hotel had shifted our booking to pay for the extra early check, which I wasn't too happy about. However after a little bit of negotiating, we managed to have that waiived. (I was prepared to wait 5hrs in the lobby until the appropriate check in time).The person that stands out the most was the conceirge. He knew practically everything about where to go and what to do.Having a Towers reservation we were picked up from the airport in a Porsche Cayenne S... Quite a welcome to my first trip to Dubai.I didnt visit the gym, but the pool is nice, and was never too busy. Though some may find it small. The hotel interior is lovely, though I am told its is not as grand as some of the hotels further out of the city.The Lobby restaurant serves excellent food.The Abra crossings are about a 15min walk down the creek, and there is a stop for the air-con boat about 5mins walk away. There is also a Bank next door for cash withdrawals if you require.Location wise, the hotel is on the Deira side of the river, so is quick to travel to from the gold souk, though anywhere else on the otherside of the Creek requires the taxis to cross over one of the two bridges, which lengthens commutting time a fair bit.In a nutshell, really nice hotel, nice views, good location, awesome service!	
Nov 25 2008 	Not what it seems - smile politely then walk away	From before I arrived until the moment I left, this was a horror story, with one redeeming feature. let's get that out of the way right now - the room was fantastic; a Creek view in the Towers - if after reading all these reviews you decide to stay here, make sure you get Room 714!1. Starwood offer a Best Price Guarantee, though I beat the rate quoted by the Hotel by 37%. To prove the rate, I had to make the booking, which then involved a 15% (First Day) cancellation fee. Starwood offered to match the rate I had paid and then beat it by 10% - which would of course have still cost me 5% overall. I asked if this discounted rate or % could be commuted to a future reservation in the same hotel and was told that it couldn't. So, don't trust Starwood's promises then...2. Internet for 13 days was charged 3 times at AED700, which is what I pay for a year at home. That is the weekly rate - I was charged 3 times, but my stay was less that 2 weeks. Go figure! The internet connection is crushingly slow and the hotel are not interested in resolving it, even for AED2,100 (£400).3. My room rate included breakfast and when I arrived there was a letter in the room advising that this could be selected from the Room Service menu. For the first 4 days this was fine, then on the 5th the Room Service guy told me that the policy had changed and I would have to eat in the restaurant. Fine, but why leave it to me to find out? Couldn't they manage expectations a bit better?4. I confirm that a single Snickers or Choclolate bar costs AED32 (£6); so does a packet of chips, nuts, a can of Coke or a bottle of water. I expect Ice Cubes do too, but - as with all the other items - there is no price list and you only find out at checkout.5. 12 black &amp; white pages cost me AED95 (£18) to print out; forget either the in-house printMe service or emailing your document to the Business Centre - the internet connection is too slow and they deny ever receiving it. Get a memory stick and go down in person.6. Huge farce sending a single page fax to Hong Kong - ended up having to dial it myself and having an argument with the Business Center staff about the number. For this privilege - AED35 (£6.75)7. Don't expect any help with your bags after checkout; it's 50 metres to the door, and you will remember every one of them. Door staff surly and refuse to hail local cabs, only the retained limos. Traffic outside the hotel can be very congested.8. Massage and Spa centre agreed a surprise package and schedule for my girlfriend face-to-face with me, then when she turned up for her surprise she was told they were busy, kept waiting for an hour and then turned away and told to come back the next day. She didn't.9. I shouldn't complain about the complimentary fruit bowl, as it was free. I'll therefore just mention that the strawberries had mould on them, and I took them down to reception to prove it.10. Multiple local phone calls charged on my bill; very cheap, but I didn't actually make any local calls. Don't know what was going on there.Conclusion - rubbish and way too much top notch competition in the immediate area (Hilton, Radisson SAS etc) - and I will certainly never stay there again. Oddly, the far cheaper 4 star Four Points by Sheraton in Bur Dubai is much nicer, if apparently less splendid.	
